<section class="u-py-40 u-bg-light">
  <div class="o-container u-max-width-800 u-mx-auto">
    <h1 class="c-heading u-mb-12">Features</h1>
    <p class="u-text-lead u-mb-0">
      MIND is a small, opinionated language for numerical computing, with
      tensors, autodiff, and MLIR integration built into the core.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="u-py-40">
  <div class="o-container u-max-width-960 u-mx-auto">
    <div class="o-layout o-layout--gutter-lg">
      <div class="o-layout__item u-1/3@md">
        <div class="c-card u-p-24 u-h-100">
          <h2 class="c-heading c-heading--4 u-mb-8">
            Native tensors &amp; autodiff
          </h2>
          <p class="u-text-sm u-mb-12">
            Tensors are first-class types with static shapes, dtypes, and broadcasting rules.
            Reverse-mode autodiff is a core language feature – not a third-party add-on.
          </p>
          <ul class="c-list u-text-sm u-mb-0">
            <li>Tensor type system (shape, dtype, symbolic dims)</li>
            <li>grad(loss, wrt=[...]) syntax</li>
            <li>Preview mode and gradient inspection</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="o-layout__item u-1/3@md">
        <div class="c-card u-p-24 u-h-100">
          <h2 class="c-heading c-heading--4 u-mb-8">
            MLIR-powered performance
          </h2>
          <p class="u-text-sm u-mb-12">
            MIND lowers into a compact IR that can be exported to MLIR, optimized, and
            executed via multiple backends.
          </p>
          <ul class="c-list u-text-sm u-mb-0">
            <li>Textual MLIR export from the CLI</li>
            <li>Integration with <code>mlir-opt</code> and CPU runners</li>
            <li>JIT, GPU, and AOT build modes behind features</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="o-layout__item u-1/3@md">
        <div class="c-card u-p-24 u-h-100">
          <h2 class="c-heading c-heading--4 u-mb-8">
            Simple, modern syntax
          </h2>
          <p class="u-text-sm u-mb-12">
            The language is intentionally small: let-bindings, expressions, tensor
            intrinsics, and a few core control constructs.
          </p>
          <ul class="c-list u-text-sm u-mb-0">
            <li>Predictable, expression-oriented semantics</li>
            <li>Readable error messages with spans</li>
            <li>Deliberately small standard library surface</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="u-py-40 u-bg-subtle">
  <div class="o-container u-max-width-960 u-mx-auto">
    <div class="o-layout o-layout--gutter-lg o-layout--middle">
      <div class="o-layout__item u-1/2@md">
        <h2 class="c-heading c-heading--3 u-mb-12">Runtime &amp; execution modes</h2>
        <p class="u-mb-12">
          The same program can be inspected as a tensor preview, executed via CPU kernels, or
          exported as MLIR for advanced compilation pipelines.
        </p>
        <ul class="c-list u-mb-0 u-text-sm">
          <li>Preview mode (shape/dtype/fill only)</li>
          <li>CPU execution kernels (optional feature)</li>
          <li>MLIR JIT / GPU / build pipelines</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="o-layout__item u-1/2@md">
        <div class="c-card u-p-24">
          <pre class="c-code-block"><code class="language-bash"># Preview MLIR
mind eval --emit-mlir 'let x: Tensor[f32,(2,3)] = 1; x * 2'

# Execute with CPU backend (feature gated)
mind eval --exec cpu '...'

# Build artifacts
mind build --emit-mlir-file out.mlir --emit-llvm out.ll</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

